  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's property market attracts interest from buyers based overseas and from temporary visa holders living in Australia. For most sellers, the process of transacting with a foreign buyer is straightforward, but there are legal requirements and financial implications on the buyer's side that can affect your campaign, your contract conditions, and your settlement timeline. Understanding them puts you in a better position to assess offers and negotiate effectively.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who counts as a foreign buyer?</h2>
      <p>For property purchase purposes, a foreign person is anyone who is not an Australian citizen, an Australian permanent resident, or a New Zealand citizen. This includes temporary visa holders, such as students, skilled workers on employer-sponsored visas, and working holiday visa holders, as well as overseas investors who have no current right of residence in Australia. Importantly, a person can be living and working in Australia full time and still be classified as a foreign person if they hold only a temporary visa.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is FIRB and when does it apply?</h2>
      <p>The Foreign Investment Review Board, known as FIRB, is the body that assesses and approves foreign investment in Australian real estate. Most foreign persons are required to apply to FIRB for approval before purchasing residential property in Australia. Purchasing without approval is unlawful and can result in the transaction being unwound by the government. In practice, most serious foreign buyers are aware of this requirement and apply early in their property search.</p>

      <p>FIRB approval has a limited scope: it approves the specific buyer to purchase a specific type of property. It does not guarantee approval for any property, and it expires if not used within a set period. A buyer who holds FIRB approval for an existing dwelling can proceed quickly once they find the right property. A buyer who has not yet applied will need to factor the approval timeline into any contract they sign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How does FIRB affect the seller?</h2>
      <p>The seller is not responsible for the buyer's FIRB compliance. The obligation rests entirely with the buyer. However, a seller who is unaware of FIRB requirements can be caught out in a couple of ways.</p>

      <p>First, if a foreign buyer enters into a contract without obtaining FIRB approval and approval is later refused or the buyer fails to apply, the contract may be voidable. This creates uncertainty and potential delay, particularly if you have already removed the property from the market. Some sellers address this by including a special condition in the contract requiring FIRB approval to be obtained within a specified period, making it a formal condition rather than an assumed background obligation.</p>

      <p>Second, the FIRB approval timeline affects the conditions period. Standard applications are generally processed within 30 days, but complex cases or high-value acquisitions can take longer. If your contract has a 14-day finance and conditions period and the buyer has not yet applied for FIRB, you may face a request for an extension that you had not anticipated. Knowing this before you accept the offer lets you negotiate the conditions period realistically from the start.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Queensland's additional foreign acquirer duty</h2>
      <p>Separate from FIRB, Queensland imposes an additional foreign acquirer duty (AFAD) on property purchases by foreign persons. This is charged on top of the standard transfer duty that all Queensland buyers pay. The AFAD rate is currently 8% of the purchase price. On a $1 million purchase, this adds $80,000 to the buyer's total duty liability, over and above the transfer duty they would otherwise pay. On a $2 million purchase, the additional cost is $160,000.</p>

      <p>This is a significant acquisition cost that affects how foreign buyers approach pricing. A domestic buyer and a foreign buyer looking at the same property face materially different total acquisition costs. In a competitive campaign, this can affect whether foreign bidders are willing to bid to the same level as domestic buyers, particularly at higher price points where the AFAD becomes a large absolute number.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the practical implication is that while foreign buyers extend the potential buyer pool, particularly for properties with strong international appeal, the AFAD means foreign buyers may need to price their offers net of that additional cost. Understanding this helps you interpret offers rather than being surprised by them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should ask when a foreign buyer makes an offer</h2>
      <p>Before accepting or negotiating an offer from a buyer you believe to be a foreign person, it is worth confirming two things. First, whether they already hold FIRB approval for the property type they are purchasing. If they do, the approval process is not a variable in your timeline. If they do not, how long they expect it to take and whether your contract will include a FIRB condition.</p>

      <p>Second, confirm that they are working with a solicitor who understands the FIRB process. A buyer who arrives at the conditions stage without legal advice on FIRB compliance creates more risk for your transaction than a buyer who has already navigated that step. Your own solicitor or conveyancer can help you structure the contract conditions to give appropriate protection without unnecessarily disadvantaging a genuine foreign buyer who is simply at an earlier stage of the approval process.</p>

      <p>The broader point is that foreign buyers are a legitimate and often highly motivated part of the Brisbane property market. Properties in inner-east suburbs with strong lifestyle credentials, school catchment access, or proximity to the CBD have genuine international appeal. Managing the FIRB and duty considerations well means you can capture that interest without letting process issues complicate your settlement.</p>

